mod LambdaBlock
  ###
  Multi-statement lambda bodies (v0.22.0).

  In argument positions where the indented-block form is not usable,
  Cure accepts two explicit multi-statement forms for anonymous
  functions: a brace-delimited `{ s1; s2; final }` and an
  `end`-terminated `s1; s2; final; end`. Both compile to the same
  `{:block, meta, exprs}` AST node that the v0.19.0 indented form
  produces, so the rest of the compiler treats them uniformly.
  ###

  ## Single-expression lambda stays the default.
  fn bump(x: Int) -> Int =
    let f = fn(n) -> n + 1
    f(x)

  ## Brace form: statements separated by `;`, final expression is the result.
  fn brace(x: Int) -> Int =
    let f = fn(n) -> { let doubled = n + n; doubled + 1 }
    f(x)

  ## end-terminated form: same semantics, different surface syntax.
  fn ended(x: Int) -> Int =
    let f = fn(n) -> let doubled = n + n; doubled + 2; end
    f(x)

  ## Entry point used by `mix cure.check.examples`.
  fn main() -> Int =
    bump(10) + brace(10) + ended(10)
